# Federated & Sync-Tracked Deletions Use Tombstones

Any entity that participates in mobile delta-sync (driven by an `edited_utc` cursor) or in cross-jurisdiction federation **must not be physically removed in normal business flows**. Deletes are recorded by setting `deleted_utc` and bumping `edited_utc` so the deletion propagates through the same channels as any other edit.

## Why

Sync requires the invariant **absence is never information; presence-of-a-tombstone is**. If a row is gone in jurisdiction A but still exists in jurisdiction B (or on a mobile client), A has no way to tell whether the row was deliberately deleted or simply hasn't been replicated yet:

- The mobile client pulling `since: T` only sees what changed; it can't observe what *vanished*.
- Reconciliation (`findUnreplicated`) and the skew healer treat missing rows as insert-time gaps to be re-replicated — exactly the wrong behavior for a deliberate removal.
- `updateManyPartial` against a missing row silently no-ops, hiding the divergence.

A tombstone (`deleted_utc != null`) is just another edit: it flows through parent edit cascades (or their analog), surfaces in the next delta-sync response, and gives every consumer — local rows, remote rows, mobile clients — a single explicit signal.

## Pattern to Avoid

```typescript
// BAD — physical delete on a dual-homed entity
async cancelParticipant(participant: DualHomedParticipant): Promise<void> {
   await this.entities.participantManager.delete(participant);
   // mobile delta-sync never sees this; remote-jurisdiction row is now orphaned;
   // reconciler will eventually try to "heal" the missing row by re-replicating it.
}

// BAD — upserting around a missing row to "fix" sync drift
await broker.updateManyPartial(jurisdictionId, filter, update, { upsert: true });
// resurrects rows another jurisdiction may have legitimately tombstoned.
```

## Correct Pattern

```typescript
// GOOD — tombstone + cascade
async cancelParticipant(participant: DualHomedParticipant): Promise<void> {
   const now = new Date();
   await this.brokers.participant.updateManyPartial(
      participant.local_jurisdiction_id,
      { _id: participant._id },
      { $set: { deleted_utc: now, edited_utc: now, updated_utc: now } },
   );
   // Cascade fans the edited_utc bump out so every sibling row + the mobile
   // delta-sync sees the tombstone in the next pull.
   this.cascadeService.cascade(parentEntity, now);
}
```

## Rules

- **No `delete()` / `deleteOne()` / `findOneAndDelete()` on federated or sync-tracked entities.** Use `deleted_utc`.
- **No `upsert` on `updateManyPartial`** for federated entities — a missing row is either an insert-time gap (handled by reconciliation) or a tombstone (handled by reading `deleted_utc`). Either way, resurrection is wrong.
- Mobile-facing projections that filter out tombstones must do so explicitly (`deleted_utc: { $exists: false }`) and document why; the field itself stays in the entity model.
- Hard physical deletion is reserved for explicit GDPR/DSAR/account-deletion processors, not normal business logic.

